column16:
Welcome to our HIT!

 

DESCRIPTION: We are a team at the University of California, Los Angeles. In today's study, you will fill out a survey. Nothing is designed to be experienced as unpleasant or “weird” in any way. In fact, no parts of this HIT involves sensitive or invasive information, tasks, or questions. The study will take around 5-7 minutes.

 

COMPENSATION: You will be paid $0.75 for your participation today.

 

PLEASE NOTE: This study contains a number of checks to make sure that participants are finishing the tasks honestly and completely. As long as you read the instructions and complete the tasks, your HIT will be approved. If you fail these checks, your HIT will be rejected.

 

CONFIDENTIALITY: Your Mechanical Turk Worker ID will be used to distribute payment to you but will not be stored with your data. Please be aware that your MTurk Worker ID can potentially be linked to information about you on your Amazon public profile page, depending on the settings you have for your Amazon profile. We will not be accessing any personally identifying information about you that you may have put on your Amazon public profile page. Any reports and presentations about the findings from this study will not include your name or any other information that could identify you. We may share the data we collect in this study with other researchers doing future studies – if we share your data, we will not include any information that could identify you.

 

SUBJECT’S RIGHTS: Your participation is voluntary. You may stop participating at any time by closing the browser window or the program to withdraw from the study. Partial data will not be analyzed.

 

For additional questions, you may contact: Franklin Shaddy (franklin.p.shaddy@gmail.com).



For questions about your rights as a participant, you may contact: UCLA Office of the Human Research Protection Program (participants@research.ucla.edu). 

   

Please indicate, in the box below, that you are at least 18 years old, have read and understood this consent form, and agree to participate in this HIT. If you choose not to participate, please exit the screen now.

Inserting the parenthetical explanation into the answer options makes the sentence more difficult to comprehend. This is in part due to the fact that it is a poor stylistic decision that would make a sentence hard to understand in almost any other context. This issue is compounded by the fact that wording your overall query as "What mistake should they prevent?" inverts the usual research study paradigm of asking something more neutral along the lines of "Which option do you prefer?". After that, you can follow it up with something along the lines of “Devoting government resources to ensuring that the city reduces the amount of unmerited fines by 10%.” and “Devoting government resources to ensuring that the city increases the amount of merited fines by 10%.” If I had more time to improve the wording, I could probably have come up with something better.
Basically, while one can definitely understand what you are trying to ask, I would strongly suggest altering the formatting in a way that controls for the above factors.
